# Backend Conventions

## PageModel Pattern

```csharp
// ✅ GOOD — inject services, validate, delegate
public class CreateLessonModel(ILessonService lessons) : PageModel
{
    [BindProperty]
    public LessonInput Input { get; set; } = new();

    public async Task<IActionResult> OnPostAsync()
    {
        if (!ModelState.IsValid) return Page();
        await lessons.CreateAsync(Input, User);
        return RedirectToPage("Index");
    }
}

// ❌ BAD — DbContext and business logic directly in the page
public class CreateLessonModel(AppDbContext db) : PageModel { /* ... */ }
```

## Entity Framework Core (SQLite)

- Register `DbContext` with `options.UseSqlite(connectionString)` in `Program.cs`.
- Use async methods (`ToListAsync`, `SaveChangesAsync`) in all I/O paths.
- Configure relationships, indexes, and constraints in `OnModelCreating` — not via data annotations alone.
- Never hand-edit migration designer files; regenerate with `dotnet ef migrations add`.

## ASP.NET Core Identity

- Extend `IdentityUser` only when extra profile fields are required.
- Use `[Authorize]` on pages that serve educational content; `[AllowAnonymous]` only for login/register/error pages.
- Prefer policy-based authorization (`[Authorize(Policy = "...")]`) over hard-coded role checks in views.

## Error Handling & Validation

- Use Data Annotations or FluentValidation on input models bound to pages.
- Return `Page()` with `ModelState` errors for validation failures; use `RedirectToPage` after successful mutations (PRG pattern).
- Log exceptions in services; surface user-friendly messages via `TempData` or `ModelState`.

## DI Registration

Register services in `Program.cs` with appropriate lifetimes:

```csharp
builder.Services.AddScoped<ILessonService, LessonService>();
```
